2 unit Scallions
1 unit Red Onion
4.5 tablespoon Sour Cream
5 teaspoon White Wine Vinegar
10 ounce Shrimp
4 ounce Bok Choy and Napa Cabbage
2 tablespoon Szechuan Paste
1 unit Chicken Stock Concentrate
1 unit Crispy Fried Onions
Salt
Pepper
1 tablespoon Butter

• Wash and dry produce.
• Trim and thinly slice scallions, separating whites from
greens; finely chop greens. Halve, peel, and dice half the
onion (whole onion for 4 servings) into ½-inch pieces.
• In a small bowl, combine scallion greens, two packets of
sour cream, and 1 tsp vinegar (four packets of sour cream
and 2 tsp vinegar for 4). Stir until smooth. Season with salt
and pepper.

• Rinse shrimp* under cold water; pat dry with paper
towels. Cut into ¾-inch pieces.
• Melt 1 TBSP butter (2 TBSP for 4 servings) in a large pot
over medium heat. Add diced onion and scallion whites;
cook, stirring, until softened and translucent, 4-6 minutes.
• Increase heat to medium high. Add shrimp and bok choy
and napa cabbage; cook, stirring, until veggies are wilted
and shrimp are opaque and mostly cooked through,
2-4 minutes (shrimp will finish cooking in the next step).

• To pot with shrimp and veggies, stir in Szechuan paste,
stock concentrate, half the remaining vinegar (all for
4 servings), and 1¼ cups water (2½ cups for 4). Bring to a
simmer; cook, stirring, until shrimp are cooked through,
1-2 minutes more.
• Remove pot from heat; stir in remaining plain sour cream.

• Divide soup between bowls; top with scallion sour cream
and crispy fried onions. Serve.

***Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.***